"Li N., Chen X., Liu F.","Two Necessary Conditions for the Glacial-Interglacial Cycles in the Quaternary",2010,"Acta Meteorologica Sinica","24","6",,"657","670",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79952758965&partnerID=40&md5=75584b000c78de544eb5f43ceb58ea8c","School of Atmospheric Sciences, Nanjing University, Nanjing 210093, China; Institute of Climate and Global Change Research, Nanjing University, Nanjing 210093, China","Li, N., School of Atmospheric Sciences, Nanjing University, Nanjing 210093, China, Institute of Climate and Global Change Research, Nanjing University, Nanjing 210093, China; Chen, X., School of Atmospheric Sciences, Nanjing University, Nanjing 210093, China, Institute of Climate and Global Change Research, Nanjing University, Nanjing 210093, China; Liu, F., School of Atmospheric Sciences, Nanjing University, Nanjing 210093, China","Milankovitch Theory shows that glacial-interglacial cycles in the Quaternary are related to the variation of solar insolation forcing linked to the earth's astronomical parameters. However, the summer insolation at northern high latitudes, usually considered as the main external forcing for the ice age as Milankovitch pointed out, is marked by the 19and 23-ka precession periodicities, which is not consistent with the glacialinterglacial cycles. On the other hand, recent studies indicate that the annual mean insolation dominated by the obliquity is also an important external forcing in glacial cycles. In this paper, it is assumed that the glacial oscillation is regulated simultaneously by the annual mean insolation at northern high latitudes related to obliquity and the noon insolation at summer solstice at the ice-line latitude related to precession. Only when both of them exceed some thresholds, does the ice sheet start to melt continuously to induce the global warming and deglaciation. Furthermore, the periodicity transition of glacial cycles at mid-Pleistocene was a natural change when the ice sheet thickness altered. A conceptual model based on this idea gives encouraging results compared with the isotopic data.","Mid-pleistocene transition; Milankovitch theory; Quaternary glaciation; Solar insolation forcing","deglaciation; glacial-interglacial cycle; glaciation; global warming; ice sheet; Milankovitch cycle; paleoclimate; Pleistocene; Quaternary",,,,,,"Adhemar, J.A., (1842) Revolutions de la mer: Déluges Périodiques., pp. 1-184. , Carilian-Goeury et V Dalmont; Agassiz, L., Upon glaciers, moraines, and erratic blocks: Address delivered at the opening of the Hel-vetic Natural History Society at Neuchatel (1838) New Philos. J. Edinburgh, 24, pp. 864-883; Ashkenazy, Y., Tziperman, E., Are the 41-kyr glacial oscillations a linear response to Milankovitch forcing? (2004) Quaternary Science Reviews, 23, pp. 1879-1890; Ashkenazy, Y., Tziperman, E., Scenarios regarding the lead of equa-torial sea surface temperature over global ice volume (2006) Paleoceanography, p. 21. , doi: 10.1029/2005PA001232; Berger, A., Long-term variations of the earth's orbital elements (1977) Celestial Mechanics, 15, pp. 53-74; Berger, A., Long-term variations of daily insolation and Quaternary climatic changes (1978) J. Atmos. Sci, 35, pp. 2362-2367; Berger, A., Milankovic astronomical theory of paleoclimates: A modern review (1980) Vistas In Astronomy, 24, pp. 103-122; Berger, A., Astronomical theory of paleoclimates (1994) Topics In Atmospheric and Interstellar Physics and ChemIstry, pp. 411-452. , Cl. Boutron, Ed., Les Ulis: Les Editions de Physique; Berger, A., Pestiaux, P., Accuracy and stability of the Quaternary terrestrial insolation (1984) Milankovitch and Climate, pp. 83-112. , A. Berger, J. Imbrie, J. Hays, G. Kukla, and B. Saltzman, Eds., D. Reidel Pub. Co., Dordrecht; Berger, A., Loutre, M.F., Insolation values for the climate of the last 10 million years (1991) Quaternary Science Reviews, 10, pp. 297-317; Berger, A., Loutre, M.F., Tricot, C., Insolation and earth's orbit